                                  Lecture      Cultural Exchange in the Languages and Literatures of Medieval Spain                  Open to the Public                                    Date                   Tuesday, October 29, 2013                                                             Time           6:00-7:30pm                                                     Location           19 Washington Square North, New York                     View map                                                                            The Iberian Peninsula (what is now Spain and Portugal) during the Middle Ages was a cultural, linguistic, and religious crossroads where Islam, Christianity, and Judaism were in constant contact. This lecture explores five examples of what this world looked like through its literature, drawing on Arabic, Hebrew, Latin, Spanish, and other Iberian Romance languages.                                   Lecture      Cultural Exchange in the Languages and Literatures of Medieval Spain                  Open to the Public                                    Date                   Tuesday, October 29, 2013                                                             Time           6:00-7:30pm                                                     Location           19 Washington Square North, New York                     View map                                                                            The Iberian Peninsula (what is now Spain and Portugal) during the Middle Ages was a cultural, linguistic, and religious crossroads where Islam, Christianity, and Judaism were in constant contact. This lecture explores five examples of what this world looked like through its literature, drawing on Arabic, Hebrew, Latin, Spanish, and other Iberian Romance languages. Visiting faculty from New York may teach a course a year, and have also participated in the Graduate Research Conference in spring. M.A. Faculty & Collaborators Luisa Elena Alcalá | Ph.D. 1998 (art history), Institute of Fine Arts, New York University. Spanish and Latin American art history, curatorial studies, transculturation and visual studies. José Amenós | Ph.D. 2010 (Hispanic philology), UNED. Pragmatics and second language acquisition, semantic and pragmatic interface, cross-linguistic variation, time and aspect in verb usage, audiovisual comprehension, film and language instruction. Carmen Bordón | DEA, 2007 (Romance philology), Universidad Complutense, Madrid. Researcher, Consejo Superior de Investigaciones Científicas (CSIC). Second language acquisition, phonetics and phonology, field research on linguistic maps of Spain and Europe. María Castillo | Ph.D. 2008 (Hispanic languages and literatures) New York University. Twentieth-century Latin American narrative and theatre. Nation-building, dictatorship and Southern Cone literature. Rafael Castillo | Ph.D. 1988 (Hispanic philology), Universidad Complutense, Madrid; Ph.D. 1975 (Spanish), University of Illinois (Urbana-Champaign). Linguistics and stylistics, history of the Spanish and Portuguese languages, Hispanic literature, reception theory, translation studies.  Jacqueline Cruz | Ph.D. 1993 (Hispanic languages and literatures), University of California - Los Angeles. Critical theory, visual and film studies, Hispanic literatures, gender and women’s studies; contemporary Spanish culture, recovery of historical memory, the avant-gardes. Julia Doménech | Ph.D. 1997 (art history), Universidad Autónoma de Madrid. Modern and contemporary art history, power and representations of the body, gender and women’s studies, visual studies and photography. Armando Figueroa | Ph.D. 1990 (Hispanic language and literature), Columbia University. Twentieth-century Latin American literature, the boom and post-boom literature, journalism and the media, mass culture and postmodernism. Soledad Gálvez  | Ph.D. 2002 (Latin American literature), Stanford  University. Assistant Director of Academic Affairs and M.A. Coordinator  (concentration in Literary and Cultural Studies), NYU Madrid. Latin American  literature and culture of the 19th-21st centuries. Modernities and  colonialities. Critical theory.     Mariano Gómez Aranda | Ph.D. 1992 (philosophy and literature), Universidad Complutense, Madrid. Researcher, Consejo Superior de Investigaciones Científicas (CSIC). Middle Ages in Spain, science and philosophy in Christian, Jewish and Islamic cultures in Medieval Spain, Spanish cultural history. José Manuel Igoa | Ph.D. 1991 (psychology), Universidad Complutense de Madrid. Psycholinguistics, cognitive psychology, lexical and syntactic processing in second language acquisition, language impairment and sentence processing.  Francisco Layna | Ph.D. 1994 (Hispanic philology), Universidad Complutense, Madrid. Golden Age Spain, history and literary history, comparative literature and philosophy, Quijote, humor and the burlesque.       María  López Díez | Ph.D. (architecture), Universidad Autónoma de Madrid. Architecture  and development of the modern city from a historical perspective, contemporary  design.      Javier Ortiz | Ph.D. 1994 (English Literature), SUNY-Binghamton. Professor, Universidad Autónoma de Madrid. Comparative literature, English language and literature, translation studies and interpretation. José Pazó | Ph.D. 1989 (Romance philology), Universidad Autónoma, Madrid. Professor, Universidad Autónoma de Madrid. Spanish syntax, lexicon, and morphology, dialectology and sociolinguistics, translation studies and semiotics. Translator from English, French and Japanese languages into Spanish. Isabel Pereira | Ph.D. 1995 (second language acquisition and teacher education), University of Illinois (Urbana-Champaign); Assistant Director of Academic Affairs, NYU Madrid. Foreign language teaching and acquisition, applied linguistics.
